[1]
Date: Mon 26 Aug 2002
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Agence France Press, via Newsline, Sun 25 Aug 2002 [edited]

Bangladesh: Military Mobilized to Assist Control of Outbreak
--------------------------------------------------
Bangladesh's military has been ordered to help civilian medics tackle an
outbreak of dengue fever that has so far left 35 people dead and nearly 3000
ill, an official said on Sun 25 Aug 2002. "The military would help in
containing the outbreak of dengue fever and also in keeping the city clean,"
the health ministry official said.The army medics would also set up
temporary camps if needed, he said. The order to enlist the aid of the
military came on Sat 24 Aug 2002 from Prime Minister Khaleda Zia at a
meeting with municipal officials.
Over the past 4 days in and outside the capital Dhaka, 3 more people have
died from the fever, while nearly 3000 have so far fallen ill across the
country since last month [July 2002], a health ministry control room
spokeswoman said. "At least 67 new cases were reported by midday (Sunday)
[25 Aug 2002] in Dhaka alone," she said.
The Bangladesh health ministry admits the number of dengue infections is on
the rise, but insists there is no reason to be alarmed. Doctors have blamed
the outbreak on a dry spell following days of rain, ideal conditions for
dengue-carrying mosquitoes to breed.
In 2000, Bangladesh announced a 5-year action plan to contain dengue fever
after 5551 people contracted the disease and 93 people died. A dengue outbre
ak last year [2002] claimed 44 lives.
--
Pablo Nart
