[2]
Date: Tue 27 Aug 2002
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@derwent.co.uk>
Source: The Daily Star, Tue 27 Aug 2002 [edited]
<http://www.dailystarnews.com/200208/27/index.htm>

Bangladesh: Dengue Death Toll in Dhaka Reaches 36
-------------------------------------------------
One person died from dengue haemorrhagic fever (DHF) while 141 people were
hospitalised with dengue and DHF in the city yesterday [26 Aug 2002]. A
47-year-old man died at the BIRDEM Hospital yesterday noon. He had been
admitted to the hospital the same day. This latest casualty ups the dengue
death toll so far to 36. The total number of people hospitalised stood at
3233 yesterday, according to the dengue control room.
Meanwhile, the Dhaka City Corporation (DCC) has almost run out of
insecticide to kill the adult _Aedes_ mosquito, the vector of the disease.
According to sources at the DCC, the city authorities have asked all its 10
zones to purchase Malathion, an effective mosquito killer that has also been
recommended by the World Health Organization (WHO). "This insecticide is
cheap. One litre costs about 35 Takas against 355 Takas a litre [USD 0.62 vs
6.34] for quick-flying fogging fluid. And it is locally available. We have
decided to purchase the insecticide as the current stock will not last more
than a week," said a DCC official. "Malathion will be equally effective in
the mosquito control programme. We are now using about 3000 litres of
quick-flying fogging fluid a day," the official added.
Meanwhile, our Khulna Staff Correspondent reported yesterday that one person
died from DHF in Magura district, while 4 others were hospitalised in
Jessore General Hospital in the last 24 hours. The Khulna City Corporation
in the meantime has launched an anti-mosquito drive in the city.
Our northern region roving correspondent reports that at least one person
died in Chapai-nawabganj district and 15 others were hospitalised for DHF.
All of them were admitted to the Rajshahi Medical College Hospital (RMCH)
during the past 10 days. The RMCH authorities have opened a 'dengue corner'
to facilitate treatment of dengue patients. Of the 15 affected, only 5 are
now undergoing treatment at the 'dengue corner' of the RMCH while the rest
have been shifted to Dhaka. In addition, 10 more persons were being treated
at different clinics in Rajshahi city.
--
Banks, A-Lan
UK
<A-Lan.Banks@derwent.co.uk>
