[3]
Date: Mon 26 Aug 2002
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: World News Connection, via Newsline, Thu 22 Aug 2002 [edited]

Taiwan: Disease Spread Slowed in Kaohsiung City
-----------------------------------------------
The Heads of the Cabinet-level Department of Health (DOH) and the
Environmental Protection Administration (EPA) jointly traveled to Kaohsiung
on Thu 22 Aug 2002 to show their concern about the campaign against dengue
fever there. DOH Minister Lee Ming-liang and EPA Administrator Hau Lung-pin
also joined with Kaohsiung City Mayor Frank Hsieh in co-chairing a meeting
on the prevention of further spread of the mosquito-borne disease in
Kaohsiung County, Kaohsiung City & Pingtung County in southern Taiwan.
Quoting tallies compiled by the DOH's Center for Disease Control, Lee said
Kaohsiung County is the area hardest-hit by the disease, with 548 confirmed
cases so far; followed by Kaohsiung City, with 531 cases. Pingtung County
has 14 confirmed cases. As of Thursday morning [22 Aug 2002], there had been
1109 confirmed cases of dengue fever throughout the island. Kaohsiung
County, Kaohsiung City & Pingtung County jointly accounted for 1093 cases,
of which 20 were dengue hemorrhagic fever, a disease with a 10-20 percent
fatality rate. The remaining cases were reported in various cities and
counties throughout the island.
"Latest tallies show that the spread of the disease has slowed in Kaohsiung
City, but has not abated in Kaohsiung County," Lee said, adding that the
greater Kaohsiung and Pingtung areas should continue various preventive
measures to avert any possible outbreak of an epidemic. As the spread of the
disease usually does not abate until after November, both Lee and Hau urged
relevant local government agencies to join forces with the private sector in
creating a living environment free of dengue-carrying mosquitoes.
In Taipei, a third dengue case was reported on Thu 22 Aug 2002. In an effort
to prevent the disease from further spreading in the city, the Taipei City
Government's health department began to conduct free blood tests for
passengers from southern Taiwan at the Taipei Railway Station [the same
day].
The city government has also continued its anti-dengue work, including
sterilizing ditches in various residential neighborhoods. [_Aedes_ do not
breed in ditches. - Mod.JW]
--
Pablo Nart
UK
