[5]
Date: Tue 27 Aug 2002
From: Paul Lamot <PL@pandora.be>
Source: Cubanet, Mon 26 Aug 2002 [Trans. & edited by Mod.JW]
<http://cubanet.org/CNews/y02/ago02/27a2.htm>
<http://cubanet.org/CNews/y02/ago02/27a3.htm>

Cuba: 39 foci of mosquitoes found in Santos Suarez [Havana]
------------------------------------------------------
39 foci of _Aedes aegypti_ have been found in Santos Suarez, a district of
Havana. Sanitary brigades are fumigating the zone, and say that they will
be extending their activities beyond that district.
(By Armando Soler/)
[It is extremely difficult to eradicate _Aedes aegypti_, when it is
continually being reintroduced by human activity. It is indeed a good idea,
given the flight range of the mosquito (found to be several hundreds of
meters in Puerto Rico, sister island to Cuba), to extend fogging beyond the
immediate district where they were found. - Mod.JW]

Cuba: Dengue Fever Cases Imported from Guatemala and Venezuela
--------------------------------------------------------------
A Cuban doctor reports that several medical and paramedical personnel
returning from international missions in South America are hospitalized with
dengue fever in the Pedro Kouri Tropical Medicine Institute in Havana. The
main such missions are reported to be in Guatemala & Venezuela.
--
Paul Lamot
Belgium
<PL@pandora.be>
[This is not surprising, given that most Latin American countries are
suffering from dengue outbreaks at the present time. However, WHO reports
that Cuban health personnel are assisting with the current epidemic in El
Salvador, which has just reported a case of dengue type 4. If they should
return infected with this strain, & it should get out into the pockets of
_Aedes aegypti_ in Havana, Cuba will have a real problem, since it has not
previously experienced that serotype. - Mod.JW]
